# direnv

 direnv is a small bash program that allows you to load and unload environments automatically as you enter a directory. 
 This means that if you’ve got a project that uses a particular set of modules you can just add a `.envrc` file in the root of your project and add all the module load commands that you need and never miss them.

 For example, for those running ACCESS models, having a `.envrc` in the `roses/` folder can be very useful:

```bash
module use /g/data/hr22/modulefiles
module load cylc7
export PROJECT=gb02
```
So every time you `cd` into your `roses/` folder, `cylc7` gets loaded automatically and you have access to the `rose` commands. And when you leave the directory, everything is unloaded, making this *environment* independent of the rest.

Another interesting example useful when inspecting model outputs saved in `/scratch/$PROJECT/$USER/cylc-run/`:

```bash
module load netcdf
module load ncview
module use /g/data/access/modules
module load xconv
```

## Installation 

direnv is already available if you are a member of gb02. Still you need to do some configurations to use it.

1. Edit your `.bashrc` to add:

```bash
prepend_path PATH /g/data/gb02/public/tools/direnv_bin/
eval "$(direnv hook bash)"
```
2. Source the file (`source .bashrc`) or open a new terminal window.

3. Now it's ready to use!

If you are not a member of `gb02` or you prefer to install it, follow [the instructions in the official website.](https://direnv.net/)

## Using direnv

To use direnv in a project folder you need to create a `.envrc` file. You can use one of the examples above as a first approximation. 

In a `.envrc` file it is possible to load any module (including `conda/analysis3`), define system variables and add things to your `PATH`. 

1. Create a `.envrc` file inside the project folder

2. Add the modules and variables you need. Save and close the file.

3. Run `direnv allow` to *approve* the new environment. You will need to repeat this every time you update the `.envrc` file. 

4. And done, enjoy your by-project environments!